{{Infobox company | name = Bogs & Voigt | logo = Klavier Bogs und Voigt 05small.JPG | type = | industry = Pianos | fate = | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = Paul Richard Bogs and Adolf Ernst Voigt | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = Berlin | hq_location_country = Germany | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''Bogs & Voigt''' was a [[piano]] manufacturer in [[Berlin]], Germany.
It was founded 1905 and existed up to 1939. The fabrication was located in Warschauerstra√üe 70 and Boxhagenerstra√üe 16a in Berlin. The owners Paul Richard Bogs (1871-1949) and Adolf Ernst Voigt were awarded an imperial and [[royal warrant of appointment]] to the courts of [[Austria-Hungary]] and [[Spain]].<ref>{{Citation | year = 1917 | title = Handbuch des Allerh√∂chsten Hofes und des Hofstaates Seiner K. und K. Apostolischen Majest√§t. | publisher =K.k. Hof- und Staatsdruckerei | publication-place =Vienna | page =519 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> Voigt left the company in 1913, Bogs went on until the company was closed in 1939. The company built about 66.000 instruments.<ref>{{Citation | year = 1994 | title = Musikinstrumentenbau in Preussen. | publisher = Hans Schneider Verlag | publication-place = Tutzing | page = 243 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>
