{{Infobox European Parliament constituency |title = Cumbria and Lancashire North |map = Image:Europarl logo.svg |mapcaption = [[European Parliament]] logo |created = 1984 |dissolved = 1999 |meps = 1 |memberstate = United Kingdom |sources = [http://www.election.demon.co.uk/] }} Prior to its uniform adoption of [[proportional representation]] in 1999, the [[United Kingdom]] used [[plurality voting system|first-past-the-post]] for the [[Elections in the European Union|European elections]] in [[England]], [[Scotland]] and [[Wales]]. The [[European Parliament constituency|European Parliament constituencies]] used under that system were smaller than the later regional constituencies and only had one [[Member of the European Parliament]] each. The constituency of '''Cumbria and Lancashire North''' was one of them.
When it was created in England in 1984, it consisted of the [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|Westminster Parliament constituencies]] of [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]], [[Carlisle (UK Parliament constituency)|Carlisle]], [[Copeland (UK Parliament constituency)|Copeland]], [[Lancaster (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster]], [[Morecambe and Lunesdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Morecambe and Lunesdale]], [[Penrith and the Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and the Border]], [[Westmorland and Lonsdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Westmorland and Lonsdale]], [[Workington (UK Parliament constituency)|Workington]], and [[Wyre (UK Parliament constituency)|Wyre]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/ |title=David Boothroyd's United Kingdom Election Results |accessdate=2008-01-20}}</ref> In 1994, Wyre constituency was transferred to Lancashire Central, but otherwise the constituency's composition remained the same until its abolition in 1999.
