[[File:First island chain perimeter (marked in red).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The ''first island chain'' perimeter (marked in red).]] The '''first island chain''' refers to the first chain of major [[archipelagos]] out from the [[East Asian]] continental mainland coast. Principally composed of the [[Kuril Islands]], [[Japanese Archipelago]], [[Ryukyu Islands]], [[Taiwan]] ([[Formosa]]), the northern [[Philippines]], and [[Borneo]]; from the [[Kamchatka Peninsula]] to the [[Malay Peninsula]]. Some definitions of the ''first island chain'' anchor the northern end on the [[Russian Far East]] coast north of [[Sahkalin|Sahkalin Island]], with Sahkalin Island being the first link in the chain.<ref>[http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/first_island_chain Wiktionary: first island chain]</ref> However, others consider the [[Aleutians]] as the farthest north-eastern first link in the chain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/plan-doctrine-offshore.htm |title=People's Liberation Navy - Offshore Defense |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=globalsecurity.org |publisher=[[GlobalSecurity.org]] |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> The first island chain forms one of three island chain doctrines within the [[Island Chain Strategy]].
The ''first island chain'' has its purpose in [[China|Chinese]] military doctrine. The [[People's Republic of China]] views the ''first island chain'' as the area it must secure and disable from American bases, aircraft and [[aircraft-carrier]] groups, if in defending itself it must tactically unleash a [[Preemptive war|pre-emptive attack]] against an enemy. The aim of the doctrine is to seal off the [[Yellow Sea]], [[South China Sea]] and [[East China Sea]] inside an arc running from the Aleutians in the north to Borneo in the south.<ref>‚ÄúAsia's balance of power: China‚Äôs military rise: There are ways to reduce the threat to stability that an emerging superpower poses‚Äù, [[The Economist]], dated 7 April 2012.</ref> According to reports by American [[think tank]]s [[CSBA]] and [[RAND]], by 2020, China will be well on its way to having the means to achieve its ''first island chain'' policy.<ref>‚ÄúChina‚Äôs military rise: The dragon‚Äôs new teeth: A rare look inside the world‚Äôs biggest military expansion‚Äù, [[The Economist]], dated 7 April 2012.</ref>
