{{refimprove|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Switzerland}} "Je vais me marier, Marie" | image = | caption = | year = 1973 | country = Switzerland | artist = [[Patrick Juvet]] | as = [[Patrick Juvet]] | with = | language = French | languages = | composer = Patrick Juvet | lyricist = Pierre Delano√´ | conductor = [[Herv√© Roy]] | place = 12th | points = 79 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1973ch from Diggiloo Thrush] | prev = C'est la chanson de mon amour | prev_link = C'est la chanson de mon amour | next = Mein Ruf nach dir | next_link = Mein Ruf nach dir }}
'''"Je vais me marier, Marie"''' ([[English language|English]] translation: "I¬¥m getting married, Mary") was the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1973]], performed in [[French language|French]] by [[Patrick Juvet]].
In the song he gathers his friends round to "laugh and sing through the night" and he gives them the news that he "is going to be married". He is renouncing his youth and folies today, for tomorrow will be the time to think about life and children. As he will not be seeing them any more, he tells them to drink to his health and lost liberty.<ref>https://www.vagalume.com.br/patrick-juvet/je-vais-me-marier-marie.html</ref>
The song was performed eighth on the night (following [[Spain]]'s [[Mocedades]] with "[[Eres t√∫ (Mocedades song)|Eres t√∫]]" and preceding [[Yugoslavia]]'s [[Zdravko ƒåoliƒá]] with "[[Gori vatra]]"). At the close of voting, it had received 79 points, placing 12th in a field of 17.
It was succeeded as Swiss representative at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974 Contest]] by [[Piera Martell]] with "[[Mein Ruf nach dir]]".
