{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
'''Radio Cordac''' (Corporation Radiodiffusion d'Afrique Central) was a well-known [[Protestant]] [[missionary]] radio service directed to listeners throughout [[Central Africa]]. Transmissions were based in [[Bujumbura]],  [[Burundi]].  The station ran from around 1963 to 1977.<ref>[http://www.voiceofhoperadio.org/project%20background.html Voice of Hope Radio website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421065645/http://www.voiceofhoperadio.org/project%20background.html |date=2012-04-21 }}</ref>  In 1969, it was one of only two radio stations in the entire country, sending out broadcasts in French, English, [[Kirundi]] and [[Swahili language|Swahili]].<ref>Area Handbook for Burundi, Foreign Area Studies, The American University, 1969.  p. 90</ref> Radio Cordac went off the air in 1977 when the [[Burundi]] government decided to stop private radio stations and only allow government stations.<ref>[http://www.users.waitrose.com/~bdxc/africa.pdf PDF document on African Shortwave stations]</ref>  The president at the time, decided no western missionaries could stay in the country.

==History==
An American organisation by the name of Voice of Hope Radio aims to continue such broadcasts to [[Central Africa]], provided they have sufficient funds to do so.<ref>[http://www.voiceofhoperadio.org/project%20background.html Voice of Hope Radio website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421065645/http://www.voiceofhoperadio.org/project%20background.html |date=2012-04-21 }}</ref>

Radio Cordac was sponsored by [[World Gospel Mission]], Kansas Society of Friends and the [[Free Methodist Church|Free Methodists]]. In 1969, the radio station was staffed by 15 African and eight European workers.

The radio station operated a four-year training program for African students from its property in Bujumbura, Burundi. Students regularly participated in radio broadcasts.

During its operating life, Radio Cordac broadcast in English, French, Swahili, Kirundi, and other African dialects, to Burundi and five central African countries, [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congo]], [[Rwanda]], [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]] and [[Uganda]], with a potential listening audience of 10,000,000 at that time.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=860&dat=19691110&id=2b5RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hksDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4245,2676366&hl=en%20|title = The Ellensburg Daily Record Page 2, 10 November 1969 edition. Interview with Dan and Nancy Wegmueller, missionary workers with Radio Cordac.|last = Prater|first = Yvonne|date = 10 November 1969|work = |access-date = |via = Google News}}</ref>

Short wave listeners could receive Radio Cordac signals as far away as Japan. In February 1973, Radio Cordac broadcast on 3985&nbsp;kHz 75 meter band, 4920&nbsp;kHz 60 meter band, 1400&nbsp;kHz Medium Wave and 93.5&nbsp;MHz FM Band. The call sign was 9UZ 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/freeradiofun/8833683340/|title = SwL Report Nobuaki Takahashi|date = 15 February 1973|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Takahashi|first = Nobuaki}}</ref>

In a public address, given around 1975 by [[Corrie ten Boom]] , the renowned Dutch World War Two prison camp survivor and Christian speaker, said that she had visited and worked at the radio station in Bujumbura and was pleased to hear that it had reopened again, broadcasting 24 hours a day, after being closed down for two years as a result of changing political policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sermonindex.net/modules/newbb/viewtopic.php?topic_id=15978&forum=34|title = Sermon Index.net Transcript of Message by Corrie Ten Boom|date = 2 April 2007|accessdate = |website = Sermon Index.net|publisher = DS|last = |first = }}</ref>

The 1976 Interval Signal for Radio Cordac can be heard on the Burundi page at www.intervalsignals.net.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.intervalsignals.net/index.htm|title = Interval Signals Online|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

